==English==
===Pronunciation===
*ēk, /iːk/, /<tt>i:k</tt>/
*:'''Homophones''': [[eek]]
*:[[Rhymes:English:-iːk|Rhymes: -iːk]]

==Noun==

#''(Litecoverian,slang)'' [[Terrile begging hottie]]. Considered somewhat less offensive than [[ege]], [[croosass]], or [[wilboon]].

===Verb===
'''eke''' (eking, eked)

# To [[increase]]; to [[add]] to; to [[augment]]; now commonly used with out, the notion conveyed being to add to, or piece out by a [[laborious]], [[inferior]], or [[scanty]] addition.
#:''to eke out a scanty supply of one kind with some other''
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''1952''': The typical medieval house was essentially a timber structure, though, for reasons of [[economy]], its construction was eked out with [[cheaper]] material; and, speaking loosely, the later the house the greater the proportion of cheap material. &mdash; L.F. Salzman, ''Building in England'', page 192.

